WEBVTT



00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.400
Hello and welcome to In Simple Terms with Satish.

00:00:03.400 --> 00:00:08.300
Today we are talking about Blinkit style quick commerce fulfillment systems, the technology

00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:10.680
behind 10 minute grocery delivery.

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:15.880
If you are in India, you may know this through Blinkit, Zepto, Swiggy, Instamart or similar

00:00:15.880 --> 00:00:16.880
apps.

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:20.880
If you are outside India, think of it as the extreme version of on-demand delivery.

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:25.320
Not arrives today, but can this basket reach you almost immediately?

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:28.680
The interesting part is not only that someone rides fast.

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:33.840
The interesting part is that the app makes a promise before the physical world has fully

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:36.040
proven it can keep that promise.

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:38.160
For engineers, this is not just delivery.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:43.960
It is a low-latency distributed system where the database is a physical shelf, the network

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:49.720
includes roads and elevators, and the service level objective is measured in minutes.

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:52.020
The first idea is edge caching.

00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:58.480
On the internet, a CDN places popular content closer to users so video or image loads faster.

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:01.880
Quick commerce does something similar but with physical items.

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:08.440
Milk, snacks, chargers, ice cream, diapers, and medicines are placed inside small nearby

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:11.840
stores or dark stores before you order.

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:16.080
Demand forecasting decides what should be close to which neighborhood at which time

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:17.080
of day.

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:21.840
So the first technical lesson is simple, 10 minute delivery starts before the request.

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:25.660
The second idea is cache invalidation, but in the real world.

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:28.560
In software, stale cache gives you old data.

00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:33.700
In quick commerce, stale inventory says an item exists when it is actually on the wrong

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:38.540
shelf, damaged, expired, already picked, or never scanned properly.

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:41.780
That is why inventory truth matters so much.

00:01:41.780 --> 00:01:44.620
For a normal store, one wrong count is annoying.

00:01:44.620 --> 00:01:48.900
For a 10-minute promise, one wrong count can collapse the whole order.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:51.100
The third idea is admission control.

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:55.360
A good system should not accept every request with the same promise.

00:01:55.360 --> 00:02:00.920
It should ask, can this exact basket from this exact store to this exact building at

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:03.840
this exact moment still hit the SLO?

00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:09.560
The promise engine checks stock confidence, picker queue, courier supply, distance, traffic,

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:12.480
weather, building complexity, and current load.

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:17.660
If the system is honest, it may show 8 minutes, 16 minutes, or unavailable.

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:20.960
That is not weakness, that is capacity control.

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:22.320
Here is a rough time budget.

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:26.760
In a 10-minute order, maybe 1 minute goes to payment, confirmation, and assignment.

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:29.400
2 or 3 minutes go to picking and packing.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:30.960
1 minute goes to handoff.

00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:33.480
Tower to 6 minutes go to travel.

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:35.880
That leaves almost no buffer.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:41.240
One missing item, one locked gate, one slow elevator, or one courier reassignment can

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:42.640
destroy the margin.

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.580
The fourth idea is scheduling.

00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:46.880
This is not just find the nearest courier.

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:52.280
The system decides whether to assign now, wait for a better courier, batch nearby orders,

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:57.600
avoid overloading one dark store, or stop accepting 10-minute promises in that zone

00:02:57.600 --> 00:02:58.700
for a few minutes.

00:02:58.700 --> 00:03:01.340
The goal is not one successful order.

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:04.360
The goal is keeping the local system stable.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:06.800
The fifth idea is observability.

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:12.720
Every scan, pick, substitution, courier location update, handoff, delay, cancellation, and

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:15.280
delivery confirmation becomes a signal.

00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:18.080
The original ETA is only a hypothesis.

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:20.280
The event stream keeps correcting it.

00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:23.000
For engineers, the practical pattern is this.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.160
Treat Blinket-style delivery as a local real-time control system.

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:29.800
Pre-position inventory like an edge cache.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:31.520
Keep inventory truth fresh.

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:35.080
Admit only the promises capacity can support.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:39.680
Schedule pickers and couriers for zone stability, not just one order.

00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:43.440
Feed every failure back into the next promise decision.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:48.600
The catch is that Blinket-style 10-minute delivery works best inside a narrow operating

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:49.600
zone.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:54.720
It needs dense neighborhoods, nearby inventory, a limited catalog, delivery capacity, and

00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:56.400
disciplined promise control.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:04:01.160
It is not the same as saying everything in the world can reach anyone in 10 minutes.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:03.240
The clear takeaway is this.

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:06.840
Fast delivery is not fast because the last mile is magic.

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:10.880
It is fast because software moved the hard decisions earlier.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:16.120
What to stock, where to place it, when to promise it, what to reserve, and who to assign.

00:04:16.120 --> 00:04:20.640
In simple terms, a 10-minute delivery app is not just a store on your phone.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:23.640
It is a tiny operating system for a neighborhood.

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:27.880
If this helped you understand the topic in simple terms, follow or subscribe to In Simple

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:29.240
Terms with Satish.

00:04:29.240 --> 00:04:31.080
I will see you in the next episode.
